<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-03-19T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-03-19T20:00:00-05:00" n="896" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d896">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/2422: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-03-19T20:00:00-05:00">March 19,
                                    1941—8 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>179. Your 281, March 12, noon,<note n="85" xml:id="d896fn1">Not
                                printed.</note> District Court.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>The Department had understood that the District Court was located
                                north of Soochow Creek. Please inform the Department when and under
                                what circumstances the Court was moved into the American
                                sector.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>The Department assumes that, in view of the very material interest
                                which this Government has in the maintenance of the integrity of the
                                District Court, you will in the event of need exert your efforts and
                                influence with both the Settlement authorities and the concerned
                                Japanese officials to the end that the Court may be given all
                                appropriate protection.</item>
                        </list>
                        <p>Sent to Shanghai. Repeated to Chungking, Peiping.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>